      "content": "Winning and losing in Silicon Valley\nBloomberg Fully Charged News Letter,\n\n\nIan King here from the Bloomberg Tech team. Since last November, pretty much all of my waking hours â€”and a fair number of sleeping ones tooâ€” have been taken up by something that never happened: the largest deal in the history of the technology industry.\n\nAfter Broadcom's $117-billion offer for Qualcomm was finally killed by a presidential order, it sparked an immediate frenzy of analysis and questions as to what the lasting impact will be. We've written a number of stories that at least partially answer that but I'd like to share a couple more thoughts.\n\nFor one, even though Qualcomm is based in San Diego, its ethos is pure Silicon Valley. Technology leads and business follows. The invent-first, then worry-about-the-numbers mentality that drives this region was put on trial and lost, at least in the court of investor opinion.\n\nHock Tan, the CEO of Broadcom, told investors that Qualcomm's management was living in a bygone era when spending on speculative, over-the-horizon projects was the way the chip industry did things. Technology needs to grow up and earn its keep now, was the message he took to Qualcomm investors. His counterparts argued that their future was bright, even if the current situation was tough.\n\nWith two days to go before a crucial Qualcomm shareholder vote, all of Tan's nominees for his target's board were winning, Bloomberg learned. If the deal vote had gone ahead and the result had followed the early pattern, Broadcom would have won a mandate to proceed.\n\nMany of the investors I spoke to about which way they were going to vote were conflicted. In the end though, it appears most chose to take money off the table now. If that's at all representative of the broader sentiment on technology, companies will need to start showing a lot more than future promise to survive.And indeed on Friday, Paul Jacobs, former CEO and son of Qualcomm's founder, said he would leave the board and explore a deal to take the company private.\n\nIt's becoming clearer that technology's relationship with Washington is growing more complicated and unpredictable. Consider the following scenario: which of these two companies would more likely win executive and legislative support for their position in the halls of power?\n\nCompany A, founded by prominent Democratic voters with a track record of falling afoul of regulators worldwide, one that has paid billions of dollars in fines and is currently under antitrust investigation by the U.S. government.\nCompany B, which has an unbroken run of getting deals quickly through approval, whose CEO had just appeared in the Oval Office and won praise from a self-proclaimed deal-making president for pledging to bring jobs back to the U.S.\n'A' is Qualcomm and their appeal to the Committee on Foreign Investment in the U.S. in late January to look into the the deal proved decisive. `B' of course is Broadcom. Most of its employees  â€”including its CEOâ€” are based in the U.S. and are citizens and it was created by bringing together a bunch of American companies. It's still looking for answers as to why its Singapore registry â€”soon to be given upâ€” cost it the Qualcomm deal when it had no bearing on other transactions.\n\nTech companies had better pay more attention to the shifting currents of politics and realize that not everybody plays by Silicon Valley rules. â€”Ian King",
      "date": "Mon 19 Mar 2018 09:09:45 AM PDT",
      "id": "broadcom-qualcom-deal-spiked",
