      "content": "[Did a tutorial scraping US Weather Service data](https://www.dataquest.io/blog/web-scraping-tutorial-python/). Finished it with this code:\n\n```python\nimport requests\nimport pandas as pd\n\nfrom bs4 import BeautifulSoup\npage = requests.get(\"https://forecast.weather.gov/MapClick.php?lat=34.0535&lon=-118.2453\")\n#page = requests.get(\"http://forecast.weather.gov/MapClick.php?lat=37.7772&lon=-122.4168\")\nsoup = BeautifulSoup(page.content, 'html.parser')\nseven_day = soup.find(id=\"seven-day-forecast\")\nperiod_tags = seven_day.select(\".tombstone-container .period-name\")\nperiods = [pt.get_text() for pt in period_tags]\n\nprint(periods)\n\nshort_descs = [sd.get_text() for sd in seven_day.select(\".tombstone-container .short-desc\")]\ntemps = [t.get_text() for t in seven_day.select(\".tombstone-container .temp\")]\ndescs = [d[\"title\"] for d in seven_day.select(\".tombstone-container img\")]\n\nprint(short_descs)\nprint(temps)\nprint(descs)\n\nweather = pd.DataFrame({\n        \"period\": periods,\n        \"short_desc\": short_descs,\n        \"temp\": temps,\n        \"desc\":descs\n    })\nweather\n\ntemp_nums = weather[\"temp\"].str.extract(\"(?P<temp_num>\\d+)\", expand=False)\nweather[\"temp_num\"] = temp_nums.astype('int')\nprint(temp_nums)\n\nprint(weather[\"temp_num\"].mean())\n\nis_night = weather[\"temp\"].str.contains(\"Low\")\nweather[\"is_night\"] = is_night\nprint(weather)\n```\n\nThis uses the python requests library, pandas and Beautiful Soup to extract and put into a table weather service software. I can see the possibilities, now to apply it to the gang data set. I will first write a script to go through the entire site, download everything into a file, and from there run an analysis.\n\nI need to be careful not to ddos them.\n\n## Signatures\n\nI wonder what signature my scraper will leave. An important thing to consider in the future and my targets become more sophisticated -- how can I watch them while still looking like normal traffic, to reduce my observation to noise.\n\nInformation Theory, of signal and noise, do come into play here as far as I would like my opponents to experience noise while I extract the signal. Turing's stochastic warfare against the Germans.\n\n## Notes on Notes\nDay two of this particular journal, heading to Pasadena to draw at the Norton Simon.",
