      "content": "#Neo Rauch\n\nNeo Rauch is a German painter born in 1960. His work is influenced by socialist realism and the glossy over-stimulation of capitalism post-Berlin wall. I see his work as a record of the so-called \"End of History\": garish, reaching for weight it can't support, perhaps a little shallow. That is to say: Neo-Liberalism writ large. But unlike his other contemporaries (say, Jeff Koons or Mirakami) there is a sense of taste and tradition to his work that roots it.\n\nI should point out: just because I agree with Jerry Saltz that his work is a little shallow it doesn't mean that I don't like it.\n\n# Narrative\n\nI first saw a Neo Rauch painting in one of my masochistic trips to the Broad Museum in Los Angeles, California. I always leave there in a bad mood, despairing for the art world. But, among the Mirakamis and the Koons there was Rauch's Falle (Trap). I immediately fell in love-- a figurative painting with acid washed colors. I never saw a Rauch hung in the Broad museum again. It must have been some kind of mistake.\n\nSince then I have only known Rauch's work through books.",
      "date": "Thu 08 Mar 2018 12:47:27 PM PST",
